window.COURSE_DAY_DATA[8] = {
  subtitle: "Follow the money — understanding frontier lab economics shapes every product decision.",
  context: "<p>Frontier AI labs run on a structural paradox: they require billions in compute to operate, charge prices that often do not cover inference costs, and compete with incumbents (Microsoft, Google, Amazon) that can absorb losses indefinitely. The sustainable path requires: (a) model quality strong enough that customers pay a premium, (b) scale that brings inference costs down significantly, or (c) platform network effects that make switching prohibitively expensive. Anthropic pursues all three simultaneously — understanding which is working shapes every product prioritization decision.</p><p>Revenue breaks into three tiers: <strong>API access</strong> (pay-per-token, developer and enterprise market, thin margins at current prices), <strong>consumer subscriptions</strong> (Claude Pro at $20/month, high margin at scale because per-user inference cost is bounded), and <strong>enterprise contracts</strong> (negotiated volume deals with dedicated capacity and SLAs — the largest revenue category for Anthropic, driven by Fortune 500 deployments). Anthropic crossed an estimated $1B ARR in 2024. OpenAI is estimated at $3-4B ARR with subscriptions a larger share. These different revenue mixes drive different product priorities.</p><p>The cost structure is the real constraint: training a frontier model costs $50-100M+ in compute, and inference costs are sticky. This is why model distillation, quantization, and speculative decoding are active research areas — they reduce inference costs without sacrificing quality. Cheaper small models (Haiku, GPT-4o-mini) are strategically important even at low per-token revenue because their margin profile is often better than flagship models. Understanding this explains why labs prioritize efficiency, why prices decline over 12-18 months, and why free tiers always get squeezed.</p>",
  tasks: [
    { title: "Build a simplified frontier lab P&L", description: "Using public pricing and estimated user numbers, build a back-of-napkin P&L for Anthropic or OpenAI. Revenue = estimated API token volume x price + users x subscription rate. What margin does this imply? What needs to be true for the business to be sustainable at current prices?", time: "30 min" },
    { title: "Compare pricing tier structures", description: "Document Claude (Free/Pro/Team/Enterprise) and ChatGPT (Free/Plus/Team/Enterprise) tiers side by side. What does each tier include? What are the specific constraints on free? What triggers an upgrade? What does the tier structure tell you about each company's GTM strategy?", time: "20 min" },
    { title: "Investment round analysis", description: "Research Anthropic's investment rounds. What did Google and Amazon invest? What were the implied valuations? What strategic value does each investor get beyond financial return? What does the structure tell you about Anthropic's role in each investor's ecosystem?", time: "20 min" },
    { title: "Mission-commercial tension memo", description: "Write 200 words on a specific scenario where Anthropic's safety mission creates tension with commercial growth. Be concrete — not 'safety vs revenue' generically, but a specific product feature or customer request where the tension is real. How would you navigate it as a PM?", time: "10 min" }
  ],
  codeExample: {
    title: "Frontier lab unit economics calculator — JavaScript",
    lang: "js",
    code: "// Frontier lab unit economics calculator\n// Models inference cost and margin at different price points\n\nconst MODELS = {\n  'Claude Haiku':    { inPrice: 0.25,  outPrice: 1.25,  estInCost: 0.10, estOutCost: 0.40 },\n  'Claude Sonnet':   { inPrice: 3.00,  outPrice: 15.00, estInCost: 1.20, estOutCost: 6.00 },\n  'Claude Opus':     { inPrice: 15.00, outPrice: 75.00, estInCost: 8.00, estOutCost: 35.00 },\n  'GPT-4o-mini':     { inPrice: 0.15,  outPrice: 0.60,  estInCost: 0.06, estOutCost: 0.24 },\n  'GPT-4o':          { inPrice: 5.00,  outPrice: 15.00, estInCost: 2.00, estOutCost: 7.00 },\n};\n\nconsole.log('=== Estimated Gross Margin by Model ===');\nconsole.log('(Note: inference cost estimates are illustrative)');\nconsole.log('-'.repeat(55));\nconsole.log('Model'.padEnd(16), 'Revenue/1M'.padEnd(14), 'Est.Cost/1M'.padEnd(14), 'Margin%');\n\nObject.entries(MODELS).forEach(([name, m]) => {\n  const revenue = m.inPrice + m.outPrice * 0.3; // ~30% output ratio\n  const cost = m.estInCost + m.estOutCost * 0.3;\n  const margin = ((revenue - cost) / revenue * 100).toFixed(0);\n  console.log(name.padEnd(16), ('$' + revenue.toFixed(2)).padEnd(14), ('$' + cost.toFixed(2)).padEnd(14), margin + '%');\n});"
  },
  interview: {
    question: "What are the unit economics of an AI API business and how do they affect product decisions?",
    answer: "The core unit economics: revenue is tokens times price, cost is tokens times inference cost, margin is the spread. At current prices, margins on large flagship models like Opus or o3 are thin or negative — labs are buying market share and betting on inference costs declining as chips and efficiency research improve.<br><br>Three direct product implications. First, free tiers are subsidized customer acquisition, not genuinely free. Every free API call has a real cost. This means free tiers get constrained aggressively when cash burn matters — a product planning dependency you need to track. Second, enterprise volume deals lock in revenue but cap upside; PM teams face pressure to maximize utilization toward contract minimums, which shapes feature prioritization. Third, model upgrades hurt margins: better models cost more to serve, so moving users to a newer model requires either a price increase or accepting lower margin. This is a real constraint on how fast you can ship improvements to end users.<br><br>Understanding these economics makes you a more effective PM because you understand why the incentives are structured the way they are."
  },
  pmAngle: "Understanding your employer's business model is basic PM competency. At a frontier lab, that model is unusual — high compute costs, thin inference margins, and dependency on a small number of large enterprise contracts. Understand it precisely or you will make prioritization decisions that make no commercial sense.",
  resources: [
    { type: "BLOG", title: "a16z: Where AI Margins Live", url: "https://a16z.com/ai-business-models/", note: "Where AI margins actually live in the stack — required reading." },
    { type: "DOCS", title: "Anthropic Pricing Page", url: "https://www.anthropic.com/pricing", note: "Current API pricing and plan tiers — memorize the key numbers." },
    { type: "BLOG", title: "SemiAnalysis: AI Inference Costs", url: "https://www.semianalysis.com/p/the-inference-cost-problem", note: "Technical analysis of inference cost structure and how it is changing." }
  ]
};

window.COURSE_DAY_DATA[9] = {
  subtitle: "The API your products will be built on — understand every parameter before your first call.",
  context: "<p>The Anthropic Messages API is the primary interface for building on Claude. Every API call has the same structure: a <strong>model</strong> identifier, a <strong>max_tokens</strong> limit, a <strong>messages</strong> array of user/assistant turns, and an optional <strong>system</strong> prompt. The system prompt is evaluated first and sets the context for everything that follows — it is your product's persona, constraints, and domain knowledge. Keep it focused: every token in the system prompt is billed on every single request, and at scale it becomes a real cost line item.</p><p><strong>Streaming</strong> dramatically improves perceived UX. Without streaming, users stare at a blank response box until the full generation is complete — for a 500-token response, that is 3-7 seconds. With streaming, tokens appear progressively via Server-Sent Events, reducing time-to-first-token to under 500ms. The difference between waiting for the page to load and watching it type meaningfully affects completion rates and user trust. Streaming is almost always worth the additional implementation complexity for any user-facing feature.</p><p>Key operational factors: Anthropic uses a <strong>tiered rate limit</strong> system (Tier 1-4 based on cumulative spend) with separate limits for requests per minute, input tokens per minute, and output tokens per minute. Planning for scale requires knowing which limit you will hit first. The <strong>Batch API</strong> processes requests asynchronously with a 24-hour window at 50% of standard pricing — essential for offline workloads like nightly document processing, bulk classification, or running eval suites.</p>",
  tasks: [
    { title: "Make your first structured API call", description: "Call the Anthropic Messages API with: a system prompt giving Claude a specific persona, a multi-turn conversation with at least 3 turns, and a request for JSON-formatted output. Log the input and output token counts. Calculate the exact cost of this call.", time: "30 min" },
    { title: "Implement streaming", description: "Modify your API call to use streaming (stream: true). Display tokens progressively in the console or a UI. Measure time-to-first-token vs the non-streaming version. What is the UX difference? Are there cases where you would NOT use streaming?", time: "25 min" },
    { title: "Design a document analysis API architecture", description: "Sketch the full API call sequence for: user uploads a 50-page contract, asks 5 questions about it. Define: system prompt, how the document is chunked if needed, question structure, which Claude model, and estimated cost per document session.", time: "20 min" },
    { title: "API changelog review", description: "Find Anthropic's API changelog at docs.anthropic.com. Identify the 3 most significant additions in the last 6 months. For each, write one sentence on the PM implication: what product capability does it unlock?", time: "15 min" }
  ],
  codeExample: {
    title: "Messages API call analysis — JavaScript",
    lang: "js",
    code: "// Anthropic Messages API structure and cost simulation\n// In production: use @anthropic-ai/sdk in Node.js\n\nconst apiRequest = {\n  model: 'claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022',\n  max_tokens: 1024,\n  system: 'You are a contract analysis assistant. Extract key terms as JSON.',\n  messages: [\n    { role: 'user',      content: 'What are the payment terms? [Contract text here]' },\n    { role: 'assistant', content: '{\"payment_terms\": \"Net 30\", \"amount\": \"$50,000\"}' },\n    { role: 'user',      content: 'Are there penalty clauses for late payment?' }\n  ]\n};\n\nfunction estTokens(text) {\n  return Math.ceil(text.split(' ').length / 0.75);\n}\n\nconst sysTok = estTokens(apiRequest.system);\nconst msgTok = apiRequest.messages.reduce((s, m) => s + estTokens(m.content), 0);\nconst inputTok = sysTok + msgTok;\nconst outputTok = 150;\n\nconst cost = (inputTok / 1e6 * 3.0) + (outputTok / 1e6 * 15.0);\n\nconsole.log('=== API Call Analysis ===');\nconsole.log('System prompt tokens:  ', sysTok);\nconsole.log('Message tokens:        ', msgTok);\nconsole.log('Total input tokens:    ', inputTok);\nconsole.log('Estimated output:      ', outputTok);\nconsole.log('Cost per call:         $' + cost.toFixed(6));\nconsole.log('Monthly (10K req/day): $' + (cost * 10000 * 30).toFixed(2));\nconsole.log('Batch API 50% off:     $' + (cost * 10000 * 30 * 0.5).toFixed(2));"
  },
  interview: {
    question: "Walk me through how you would architect a document analysis product on the Anthropic API.",
    answer: "I would architect four layers: ingestion, context management, API integration, and output handling.<br><br>Ingestion: convert PDFs and DOCX to clean text. For documents under 150K tokens, pass the full text directly — no chunking needed with Claude's 200K context window. For larger documents, split into 100K-token chunks with 10K-token overlap to preserve cross-reference context between adjacent sections.<br><br>Context management: system prompt defines the analysis persona and output format as a JSON schema. Keep it under 2K tokens to minimize per-call overhead. User messages contain the document text plus specific questions. For multi-turn sessions, summarize prior findings rather than passing full conversation history.<br><br>API integration: Claude 3.5 Sonnet for analysis. Streaming for real-time user-facing responses. Batch API for nightly bulk processing at 50% cost. Exponential backoff for rate limit handling. Log all calls with token counts for cost monitoring.<br><br>Output handling: specify JSON schema in the system prompt. Validate every response against the schema. On validation failure, retry once with the error message passed back to Claude for self-correction. Cache outputs for identical document plus question combinations."
  },
  pmAngle: "Every PM building on Claude needs to explain the API call structure clearly — you will review integration code, debug production issues, and estimate infrastructure costs. This is not optional technical depth. It is baseline competence for the role.",
  resources: [
    { type: "DOCS", title: "Anthropic Messages API Reference", url: "https://docs.anthropic.com/en/api/messages", note: "Full API reference — read the request and response schemas end to end." },
    { type: "DOCS", title: "Streaming Guide", url: "https://docs.anthropic.com/en/api/messages-streaming", note: "How to implement SSE streaming in Node.js and Python." },
    { type: "DOCS", title: "Batch API Guide", url: "https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/build-with-claude/message-batches", note: "50% cost reduction for non-real-time workloads." }
  ]
};

window.COURSE_DAY_DATA[10] = {
  subtitle: "The dominant API in the ecosystem — understand it deeply to compare, compete, and build.",
  context: "<p>The <strong>Chat Completions API</strong> is OpenAI's core endpoint and the most widely used LLM API in the world. Its format — a messages array with role/content pairs, plus parameters like temperature and max_tokens — became the de facto industry standard that most other LLM providers mirror. Understanding it well means you can evaluate any new LLM API quickly. The critical additions: <strong>JSON mode</strong> forces the model to return valid JSON, and <strong>Structured Outputs</strong> constrains the model to a specific JSON Schema — essential for production extraction pipelines where malformed output is a production incident.</p><p>The <strong>Assistants API</strong> adds persistence and state: Threads (conversation histories stored by OpenAI), Files (uploaded documents), and built-in Tools (code interpreter for sandboxed Python, file search for retrieval). The tradeoff vs Chat Completions: Assistants is more feature-complete but more opaque. You do not control the exact context management, the exact retrieval behavior, or the exact prompt structure. For teams wanting to ship quickly without building RAG, this is a significant time saver. For teams needing auditability or cost control, the opacity is a dealbreaker.</p><p>Fine-tuning is available for GPT-4o and earlier models: upload training examples in JSONL format, trigger a job, receive a custom model endpoint. Practical thresholds: 50 examples minimum for any effect, 200-500 for reliable improvement, 2,000+ for strong domain adaptation. The limiting factor is almost always data quality, not quantity — 100 perfectly labeled examples beat 2,000 mediocre ones. Budget 80% of your fine-tuning effort for data curation and only 20% for the actual training job.</p>",
  tasks: [
    { title: "Implement structured JSON output", description: "Call the Chat Completions API with response_format set to json_object and a system prompt specifying an exact JSON schema. Extract structured data from 5 different unstructured text inputs. What is the validation failure rate? What causes failures?", time: "25 min" },
    { title: "Create an Assistant with a file", description: "Create an OpenAI Assistant with file_search enabled. Upload a PDF — a product spec, company report, or research paper. Ask 5 questions requiring document reading. Compare the answers to what you get from pasting the text directly into Chat Completions. What does each approach do better?", time: "25 min" },
    { title: "Write a Chat Completions vs Assistants decision guide", description: "Write a 1-page decision guide with a clear decision tree: when do you use Chat Completions vs Assistants API? Include: conversation state requirements, retrieval needs, debugging requirements, cost transparency, and latency. Make it something a new engineer could follow without asking follow-up questions.", time: "20 min" },
    { title: "API changelog review", description: "Check OpenAI's API changelog for the past 3 months. List the 3 most significant additions. For each: what use case does it unlock, and does it change any architectural decision you would have made 6 months ago?", time: "10 min" }
  ],
  codeExample: {
    title: "Structured output extraction pattern — JavaScript",
    lang: "js",
    code: "// Chat Completions structured extraction pattern\n// Shows JSON mode and simple response validation\n\n// System prompt that specifies exact output schema\nconst systemPrompt = [\n  'You are a funding data extraction assistant.',\n  'Always respond with JSON in exactly this format:',\n  '{\"company\": string, \"amount\": string or null,',\n  '\"stage\": string, \"investors\": [string]}',\n  'Use null for any field not mentioned.'\n].join(' ');\n\nconst inputs = [\n  'Acme Corp raised $50M Series B led by Sequoia in January 2025.',\n  'Beta AI closed a $200M round with participation from a16z and Tiger.',\n  'Startup XYZ announced pre-seed funding but did not disclose the amount.'\n];\n\n// Simulate extraction and validation\nfunction simulateExtract(text) {\n  return {\n    company: text.split(' ').slice(0, 2).join(' '),\n    amount: text.includes('$') ? text.match(/\\$[\\d,]+[MBK]*/)[0] : null,\n    stage: text.includes('Series B') ? 'Series B' : text.includes('pre-seed') ? 'Pre-seed' : 'Unknown',\n    investors: text.includes('Sequoia') ? ['Sequoia'] : text.includes('a16z') ? ['a16z', 'Tiger'] : []\n  };\n}\n\nconsole.log('Structured Extraction Results:');\nconsole.log('-'.repeat(45));\ninputs.forEach((input, i) => {\n  const result = simulateExtract(input);\n  console.log('Input ' + (i+1) + ':', input.slice(0, 55) + '...');\n  console.log('Output:', JSON.stringify(result));\n  console.log();\n});"
  },
  interview: {
    question: "What is the difference between Chat Completions and Assistants API? When would you use each?",
    answer: "Chat Completions is stateless: you send the full conversation history on every call, get a response, and manage all state yourself. Assistants API is stateful: OpenAI stores threads, files, and run history for you. The model and instructions are configured once per assistant rather than per request.<br><br>Use Chat Completions when: you need precise control over exactly what context is included, you are building simple single-turn features, you need full transparency for debugging and cost attribution, or you are building something that may need to switch LLM providers. Chat Completions is the industry standard format. Use Assistants when: you want built-in file retrieval without building a RAG pipeline, you want conversation history managed for you, or you want the code interpreter for sandboxed Python execution.<br><br>The fundamental tradeoff is control vs convenience. Assistants is faster to prototype but harder to debug — you cannot see exactly what context the model used for a given response. For production systems in regulated industries or systems requiring audit trails, Chat Completions is almost always right because you control and can log every single input."
  },
  pmAngle: "OpenAI's API design choices set industry conventions you will encounter repeatedly. Every new LLM provider you evaluate will either follow the Chat Completions format or diverge from it — and understanding why they diverge tells you a lot about their technical priorities and strategic intent.",
  resources: [
    { type: "DOCS", title: "OpenAI Chat Completions API", url: "https://platform.openai.com/docs/api-reference/chat", note: "The industry standard API format — know it cold." },
    { type: "DOCS", title: "OpenAI Assistants API", url: "https://platform.openai.com/docs/assistants/overview", note: "When persistence and built-in tools are worth the control tradeoff." },
    { type: "DOCS", title: "Structured Outputs", url: "https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/structured-outputs", note: "JSON Schema-constrained output — essential for production extraction pipelines." }
  ]
};
